Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated his tenth anniversary yesterday. President Francine Décary had a good reason for celebrating because Hema-Québec today became one of the world's safest and most effective blood- givenrs.
Most importantly, he managed to regain people's trust, which was seriously affected by the scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As known, national blood reserves treated by the Canadian Red Cross blood supply have been infected with acquired immune deficiency symptoms (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the drama and the general revolution, the Canadian government launched an official investigation under the leadership of Judge Horace Krever in February 1994, which was designed to shed light on the circumstances that led to tragedy and to put forward proposals to avoid similar events in the future.
While Judge Krever has submitted his late report, some provinces have established their own committees with the aim of designing a new blood management system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gelineau Committee carried out this task.
The Gélineau and Krever reports have led to two blood supply services in Canada: one is Hema-Québec, the other is responsible for all other provinces and the two territories.
“When Hema-Québec started its activities in 1998, people had less than 38% confidence in Quebec’s blood supply system, ” recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was doubtful.
“In the coming years, however, we managed to recover people’s trust as a result of improving the safety of blood products and our work in the field, ” Décary proudly states that, at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the population in Quebec already considered Hema-Quebece to be reliable.
However, Dr. Décary does not forget that “the trust is an extremely fragile thing ”
It has applied the precautionary principle since its establishment in Hema-Québec on 28 September 1998.
During this period, a number of cases have been discovered in Europe when the infant’s disease, that is, Creutzfeldt-Jakob’s disease, has infected people, says the doctor who has been running the company since its founding in 1998.
“We had no idea whether this disease spreads through the blood.
Therefore, we have relied on one of the most important recommendations of the Krever and Gelineau reports. On this basis, if we are uncertain and are at risk of developing serious disease, we must apply exclusion measures. In this case, it was Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which causes brain changes and thus inevitably leads to death.
Therefore, in April 1999, we did not accept blood from persons who have spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
And a few years ago, no doubt was found that the disease spreads through the blood.
This case convinced us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle,
In 1999, a technology published on the market that makes the HIV virus more sensitive to diagnosing. This is a nucleic acid test (NAT) that is directly able to detect the virus in the blood of blood donors and not the antibodies to which the virus was used.
Using the NAT test, we could shorten the window cycle, which lasts from infection until the virus can be detected in the blood using our technical tools - explains the expert.
This period could be reduced to a shorter period than one week.
Thus, there was a significant reduction in the risk that blood clots would infect blood and that this could not be detected.
These improvements significantly reduced the risk of the spread of AIDS by blood transfusion.
Today, the risk of getting HIV-infected blood is 12 million to one.
“In other words, this means that we should distribute 12 million blood products as long as someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Because Hema-Québec distributes 400-500 thousand blood products each year, it should take more than 24 years for such a case to occur and for some to be infected with HIV through a blood product.
I think that anyone can accept it now or write a blood transfusion to restore health - sets out Hema-Québec's number one leader.
“The challenge of the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
We never know what a new pathogen is getting into the system.
It was only last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, like the West Nile virus, enters the blood with insect bites.
Therefore, we need to keep on being afloat, Dr. Décary, and she stressed that Hema-Québec had to provide sufficient permanent reserves in addition to emergency supplies.
“As the population ages, demand is also growing.
Since anticancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the stock of blood donors, as the number of people in the network who can donate blood represents only 3% of the population in Quebec.
However, any healthy person, at least 18 years old, who fulfils the eligibility criteria, can have blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average 14% of applicants do not accept blood because they have been infected with AIDS or malaria, and those who have been in a country where malaria is destroyed do not qualify for blood transfusion for one year.
“With this 3%, we have enough reserves to meet hospital needs.
It's very rare we're out of stock.
But we need to increase the number of blood donors to the extent that the existing ones are older, because they can't give blood after a while.
However, people are very difficult to convince to give blood, but it is even harder to keep them and make them become regular donors of blood.
In this world of running around today, man barely has an hour to go out and give blood, ” lament Francine Décary.
Hema-Québec, an annual budget of $297 million, provides not only blood products but also human tissues, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and leather tissue, which are used for almost exclusively seriously burned persons.
These tissues are analysed, converted and frozen, then placed at Hema-Québec, which also manages a single public stem cell bank.
It is only the cord that is treated as medical waste that can be obtained with blood that is rich in stem cells, so it can also be treated with serious diseases (such as leukemia).
\"Some weeks ago, we celebrated the fact that we have been in our bank for the thousandth time, we are planning to take out more than a thousand new samples each year.
At the beginning of next year, we are probably about to start offering these for organ transplants,\" Dr. Décary explained, who said that the nebula blood recovery program is very popular these days.
“It is true that many mothers are sad about this because, because Hema-Québec does not have the option of making this complex and costly program available in every hospital in Quebec.
