Hepatitis: When should we seek medical advice?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and among the leading causes of death, chronic liver disease is mentioned in Hungary.
The number of domestic hepatitis patients is 100, but only seven thousand are treated, which is why patients often do not know that they are infected.
The designation of hepatitis is a compound name for infectious liver products caused by various viruses.
In their symptoms there are many similarities, typical of liver inflammation and yellowness, but their pathogens and the diseases they cause are different from each other.
Hepatitis viruses range in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E via the feeding channel (e.g. infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (sand, vaginal discharge, saliva).
Travelers are definitely worth protecting against A and B virus, with no vaccine against C.
Hepatitis The symptoms are two to three weeks after the intake of infected food, generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal disorder and nausea.
After this occurs yellowness on the skin and on the white of the eyes, the stools are clear, the urine becomes dark, healing can take two to three weeks.
One million people die from more severe types of disease around the world, liver cancer and liver dysfunction caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only every ten of them are infected with medication.
Hepatitis C may also have very serious consequences: if you are not treated, it can also lead to hepatic impairment and liver cancer.
Most infected people don't even know about their disease because the pathogens destroy the liver cells, in many cases only 20 to 30 years from now, the first symptoms will occur.
Thus, it is very important to carry out early prevention, regular screening.
In three groups, this type of disease is much more than average: between people undergoing blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and tattooed people.
There are currently 200 million people worldwide infected with chronic hepatitis C virus.
Since the disease may already be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is recommended that any unknown symptom be treated with a pediatrician.
In time, the disease can be cured, the virus can be removed from the body, so that the infectivity and the development of cancer can be eliminated.
30 September is the World Day of Hepatitis, which was first organized in 2004 by patient organisations around the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver inflammation, development of viruses and the importance of early recognition of the disease.
